        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1885-05-06T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1885-05-06T00:00:00-05:00" n="109" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d109">
                <head>No. 105.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Reinberg</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Porter.</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">United
                                    States Consulate-General</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Guayaquil,
                                    Ecuador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1885-05-06">
                            <hi rend="italic">May</hi> 6, 1885</date>.
                            (Received May 26.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 121.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge receipt this
                        day of Hon. Secretary Bayard’s telegram, addressed to this office, as
                        follows: “We hold Santos’s citizenship frilly established and not debatable,
                        and expect treatment accordingly. Wachusett will soon return Guayaquil
                        bearing full instructions,” and have mailed copy to Hon. Horatio K. Beach,
                        consul-general, now at Quito.</p>
                <p>I am, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>MAETIN REINBEEG,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">United States
                                Vice-Consul-General.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
